{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"840a53c4-dd27-4173-949c-ef323c838c3d","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, so here's what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish as a dotnet tool:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <TargetFramework>net8.0</TargetFramework>\n\n  <!-- Makes it a dotnet tool -->\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/repo</PackageProjectUrl>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n- **`PackAsTool`** — marks the package as a global/local dotnet tool.\n- **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI command users invoke (e.g., `my-mcp-server`).\n- **`OutputType` must be `Exe`** — tools must be console apps.\n\n### Publish workflow\n\n```bash\n# Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# Push (get your API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install & run it\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server          # runs via stdio\n```\n\nWould you like me to scaffold the project with these settings?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c635026c-f5a9-4406-8330-d0a7343c5aef","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The directory doesn't exist yet. The user is asking what they need to configure, not asking me to create the project. Let me give them guidance on what's needed to publish a C# MCP server as a dotnet tool to NuGet.org.","outputTokens":530},"id":"d6df8dbb-052e-4d62-98d9-37ac9e689a93","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:45:14.056Z","parentId":"b226cc5d-e927-4f35-920e-ea220763f549"}
